    "explanation": "We use a divide and conquer strategy, merging pairs of lists until only one remains. This gives a time complexity of O(N log k), which is more efficient than merging one by one O(N k).",
    "answer": "def solve(lists: List[Optional[ListNode]]):\nl1 = lists[i]\n        l2 = lists[i + 1] if (i + 1) < len(lists) else None\n        merged.append(self.merge2Lists(l1, l2))\n    lists = merged\n    return lists[0]\n    def merge2Lists(self, l1, l2):\n    dummy = ListNode(0)\n    curr = dummy\n    while l1 and l2:\n    if l1.val < l2.val:\n        curr.next = l1\n        l1 = l1.next\n    else:\n        curr.next = l2\n        l2 = l2.next\n    curr = curr.next\n    curr.next = l1 if l1 else l2\n    return dummy.next",
